caption: My fave wings in Chicago! Can’t wait for it to reopen!  Seen a lot of negative reviews here which seems crazy. Any time we’ve gone in, both during busy and quiet times, food has always been great! If you’re a fan of wings give their omg a try! Honestly keep driving by to see if their reopening.

I like this restaurant! They prepare first-cleass meals, their menu is decent, The cook in that spot is a real authority in the kitchen, I like very much trying all their dishes. The dishes are always fresh, the attitude towards the guests  is good. I visit often this restaurant and I not even once was discontended. I recommend it to all.

I was here after a Cubs game and it was raining heavily. No one seemed to know how to close the open space so we could avoid getting wet. It was chaotic and a friend tried to step in to help (he's tall) and the staff was upset. It was a mess. Aside from that, it's a decent spot for wings and snacks before/during/after a game.

Food was really good and reasonably priced for being so close to Wrigley Field. Ordered the cheese curds as an appetizer. They were a lot smaller than what I'm used to but still good, nevertheless. You got more of a cheese flavor without the marinara sauce. My entree I got wings and my buddy had a burger. I got the mild wings, which was pretty good dipped in the buttermilk ranch. Went a couple hours before game time so the service was very good, very attentive. Overall very good food!

We had the pulled pork sliders, the steak and cheese sandwich, the chicken salad, the guacamole, and fries. It was all terrible. The waiter asked us if everything was good but when he saw our expressions he changed the question to ‘did you get all of your food’. This seems like a perfect place for a beer before the game... just don’t eat.

We arrived and the restaurant was almost empty. After waiting 15 minutes to have a waitress come to our table to bring us menus, we ordered drinks. It took another 15 minutes for our drinks to come, so we ordered right then, since service was slow. After that, our waitress didn't come back or bring us more drinks. We tried to flag her down several times but she ignored us. Finally, after waiting 50 minutes for our food, the meal came and 2 of the 3 items were completely wrong. We sent the food back and asked for our check. The waitress was defensive and said it wasn't her fault. Then she acted like she was doing us a favor by not charging us for the food we never got.  We have been here multiple times and the food is decent (when you get it), but service has gotten worse every time. The frustration is definitely not worth it. I recommend skipping Yak-Zie's, especially on game day.

This is your typical sports bar in Wrigleyville. It's a great place to stop before or after a Cubs home game or to watch a Cubs or Blackhawks game. You get to mix and mingle with locals and visitors. It has two areas: main room when you first walk in has a lot of seating better for groups and a sun roof and the second room is smaller but has two bars. The service in my experience is better in the second room. The wait staff and bartenders are more attentive. They also have complimentary popcorn. Their wings are the menu item of choice for my other half, whereas I stick to the giant nachos. This is a fun place to be during MLB playoffs. Be sure to check their schedule during the Cubs off season because they are not open year around.

As far as a place to go before the Cub's game, I would give it 5 stars for location, but that's about it.  Tried their "World's Best" wings--not even in my top 5 that I've had before.  They were tiny wings, and you could tell they hadn't changed the fryer oil in quite some time.   Had an odd, stale, burnt oil taste.  The blue cheese dip was pretty good, and loaded with blue cheese chunks.  Possibly house made?  Also had their cheese curds--OK, but I've had fried cheese curds in Wisconsin, and these weren't even close.  Tasted more like mozzarella bits, and not real cheese curds.    Beer was cold, so that's a thumbs up.
Super Nachos were a great choice!

Yak-Zies' wings fifteen years ago were the tiniest, most ethereal, ever-so slightly crispy wings and drumsticks, darkened from the fryer, glazed with a tangy vinegary red sauce.  Now they're oversized slick baked wings you can find anywhere in Akron.  The oh-my-gosh sauce hasn't changed, but it's not enough to salvage them.  The pizza is an embarrassment-- an artless medium thick white flour crust with a glob of banked cheese on top which slides off easily over the unremarkable red sauce.   Not up to Chicago culinary standards. Avoid.

Visited Chicago from Cleveland to see Cub's game on Monday blackhawks won cup.  Got to stadium early and stopped at Yak-Sies for pregame beverage with 12 family members including several kids and grandma.  Game was cancelled at about 5:30 pm ish when it started to pour the rain.  We called our taxi and they were coming at about 8 pm because of traffic downtown.  Our waitress asked what time we were staying and we explained situation to her.  At about 7:15 pm a restaurant employee told our kids they had to leave as of 7pm.  It was still pouring outside and they told us you leave or be arrested after some argueing.  The restaurant then told our group that we could stand outside in front.  Most of the group stood under awning at the restaurant next door except grandma because she just had back surgery.  After about 20 minutes a restaurant employee came out and told her that she was bothering customers and needed to be 15 feet from building.  We spent about $300 in that place and were treated like crap.  If I come back for make up game in August I would never return toYak-sies  they were jerks to my entire family
